<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
<title>Toronto Parks &mdash; Reference Layer for OSM Editors</title>
<link rel="stylesheet" href="index.css">
<link rel="stylesheet"
      href="https://unpkg.com/leaflet@1.9.4/dist/leaflet.css"
      integrity="sha256-p4NxAoJBhIIN+hmNHrzRCf9tD/miZyoHS5obTRR9BMY="
      crossorigin="">
<script defer src="https://unpkg.com/leaflet@1.9.4/dist/leaflet.js"
        integrity="sha256-20nQCchB9co0qIjJZRGuk2/Z9VM+kNiyxNV1lvTlZBo="
        crossorigin=""></script>
<script defer src="index.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
<main>

<h1>Toronto Parks</h1>
<p class="lead">
  A reference layer of the parks, golf courses, cemeteries and other public
  green spaces published by the City of Toronto &mdash;
  <strong>{{PARK_COUNT}}</strong> polygons with names &mdash; ready to add
  to the <a href="https://www.openstreetmap.org">OpenStreetMap</a> editors
  <strong>iD</strong> and <strong>JOSM</strong> while you map.
</p>
<p class="meta">City data: {{DATA_DATE}} &middot; tiles rebuilt: {{BUILD_DATE}}</p>

<div class="attribution">
  Park data &copy; City of Toronto, published under the
  <a href="{{LICENSE_URL}}">Open Government Licence &ndash; Toronto</a>.
  Source: <a href="{{DATASET_PAGE}}">Green Spaces</a>.
</div>

<h2>Preview</h2>
<div id="preview-map" data-raster-url="{{RASTER_URL}}"></div>
<p class="meta">
  The raster layer drawn over OpenStreetMap: park boundaries with names.
  Pan and zoom to check coverage for the area you map.
</p>

<h2>Two layers &mdash; which to use</h2>
<table>
  <tr>
    <th>Vector layer</th>
    <td>Interactive. Click a polygon to read its tags
        (<code>name</code>, <code>class</code>, <code>area_id</code>).
        Best in <strong>iD</strong>.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <th>Raster layer</th>
    <td>Boundaries and park names drawn directly on the tiles. A readable
        backdrop. Best in <strong>JOSM</strong>.</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<div class="note">
  <strong>Heads-up:</strong> a park's name label only renders once the polygon
  is big enough on screen to fit it &mdash; big parks are labelled from city
  zoom, small parkettes only when you zoom in.
</div>

<h2>Add to iD</h2>
<h3>Vector layer (interactive)</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Open the iD editor and press <kbd>U</kbd> for the <em>Map Data</em> panel.</li>
  <li>Under <em>Custom Map Data</em>, open the settings and paste this URL:</li>
</ol>
<pre class="url">{{VECTOR_URL}}</pre>
<p>Zoom in, then click any park to see its tags in the inspector.</p>

<h3>Raster layer (visible names)</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Open the <em>Background</em> panel and choose <em>Custom</em>.</li>
  <li>Paste this URL template:</li>
</ol>
<pre class="url">{{RASTER_URL}}</pre>

<h2>Add to JOSM</h2>
<h3>Raster layer (recommended for JOSM)</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Open <em>Preferences &rarr; Imagery</em> and click <strong>+TMS</strong>.</li>
  <li>Paste this entry (the <code>tms[13,17]</code> prefix sets the zoom range;
      JOSM scales it up past z17):</li>
</ol>
<pre class="url">tms[13,17]:{{RASTER_URL_JOSM}}</pre>
<p>
  Give it a name such as <em>Toronto Parks</em>, click OK, then enable
  it from the <em>Imagery</em> menu. Note JOSM's placeholder is
  <code>{zoom}</code>, not <code>{z}</code>.
</p>

<h3>Vector layer (optional)</h3>
<p>
  JOSM can also add the vector tiles via <em>Preferences &rarr; Imagery</em> &rarr;
  <strong>+MVT</strong>:
</p>
<pre class="url">{{VECTOR_URL_JOSM}}</pre>

<h2>Notes</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Polygons kept from the Green Spaces dataset: parks, open green spaces,
      golf courses, cemeteries and civic squares. Traffic islands, road
      slivers and hydro corridors are filtered out.</li>
  <li>Vector tiles are pre-rendered through zoom 19; raster tiles for
      z13&ndash;17 (the editor overzooms them further).</li>
  <li>Tiles are refreshed weekly from the City's dataset (the City updates
      it monthly).</li>
  <li>This is a <strong>reference</strong> layer &mdash; verify against survey or
      imagery before copying anything into OpenStreetMap.</li>
</ul>

<footer>
  <a href="https://github.com/{{GITHUB_REPO}}">Project source on GitHub</a>
